A N A C T
RELATING TO FOOD AND DRUGS -- WHOLESALE PRESCRIPTION DRUG
IMPORTATION PROGRAM
Introduced By: Representatives Tanzi, Kislak, Hull, Morales, Potter, Ajello, Bennett,
Cortvriend, Boylan, and Cotter
Date Introduced: February 28, 2025
Referred To: House Health & Human Services
It is enacted by the General Assembly as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Title 21 of the General Laws entitled "FOOD AND DRUGS" is hereby
2 amended by adding thereto the following chapter:
3 CHAPTER 38
4 WHOLESALE PRESCRIPTION DRUG IMPORTATION PROGRAM
5 21-38-1. Authorization.
6 The wholesale prescription drug importation program ("the program") is established to
7 allow for the wholesale importation of prescription drugs from Canada by or on behalf of the state.
8 The program shall be designed in accordance with the requirements of this chapter. The program
9 may not be implemented unless the state obtains approval and certification, pursuant to § 21-38-
10 2(c), from the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
11 21-38-2. Design of program.
12 (a) Design requirements. The executive office of health and human services, in consultation
13 with appropriate federal and other state agencies, other states and interested parties, shall design
14 the program to comply with the applicable requirements of 21 U.S.C. § 384, including requirements
15 regarding safety and cost savings. The program design shall:
16 (1) Designate a state agency to become a licensed drug wholesaler or to contract with a
17 licensed drug wholesaler in order to seek federal certification and approval, pursuant to § 21-38-
18 2(c), to import safe prescription drugs and provide cost savings to consumers in the state;

1 (2) Use prescription drug suppliers in Canada regulated under the laws of Canada or of one
2 or more Canadian provinces, or both;
3 (3) Ensure that only prescription drugs meeting the federal Food and Drug Administration's
4 safety, effectiveness and other standards are imported by or on behalf of the state;
5 (4) Import only those prescription drugs expected to generate substantial cost savings for
6 consumers in the state;
7 (5) Ensure that the program complies with the transaction and tracing requirements of 21
8 U.S.C. §§ 360eee and 360eee-1, to the extent feasible and practical, prior to imported prescription
9 drugs coming into the possession of the licensed drug wholesaler, and that the program complies
10 fully with those federal requirements after imported prescription drugs are in the possession of the
11 licensed drug wholesaler;
12 (6) Consider whether the program may be developed on a multistate basis through
13 collaboration with other states;
14 (7) Prohibit the distribution, dispensing or sale of imported prescription drugs outside of
15 the state;
16 (8) Recommend a charge per prescription or another method of financing to ensure that the
17 program is adequately funded in a manner that does not jeopardize significant cost savings to
18 consumers, including adequate funding for the initial start-up costs of the program;
19 (9) Apply for and receive funds, grants or contracts from public and private sources; and
20 (10) Include an audit function.
21 (b) Rules. The executive office of health and human services shall adopt and promulgate
22 rules and regulations to design the program, in accordance with the requirements of subsection (a)
23 of this section, no later than January 1, 2026.
24 (c) Request for federal approval and certification. The executive office of health and human
25 services shall submit a request for approval and certification of the program to the United States
26 Department of Health and Human Services no later than May 1, 2026.
27 21-38-3. Implementation.
28 (a) Implementation of operation. Upon receipt of federal approval and certification under
29 § 21-38-2(c), the state agency designated to oversee the program pursuant to this chapter shall
30 implement the program as required in subsection (b) of this section. The program shall begin
31 operating no later than six (6) months following receipt of federal approval and certification.
32 (b) Requirements. Prior to operating the program, the state agency designated to oversee
33 the program pursuant to this chapter shall:
34 (1) Become a licensed drug wholesaler or enter into a contract with a licensed drug
